snippet.textDisplay: Also, here’s an idea explaining dark matter and dark energy. If matter is attracted to anti matter and anti matter is repelled from matter and anti matter is attracted to anti matter, then anti matter would be pushed out and away from our tangible matter parts of the universe and clump into anti matter parts of the universe. This would occur during the creation of virtual particle pairs. This would pull our matter part of the universe in every direction, stretching the universe as we know it. It would also account for dark matter because these anti matter-matter pairs would accelerate faster than light, making them “untraceable” by conventional means.

snippet.textDisplay:
Not really part of this video, but a shower thought I had.

Regarding merging singularities. A singularity at the center off a black hole should be a one dimensional point. Making it impossible for two to ever merge. Two points can only ever approach each other but never reach each other. Which makes it impossible for them to merge, none the less we observe black holes merge and act as if there is one singularity on the inside.
So here is my thought, what if the plank length takes part in making it so? So far the plank length seems to be a real thing. The smallest distance in the universe in which stuff like time and space still has meaning. What if the universe, regarding two approaching singularities, regards them as one (or they do merge or something along those lines) the moment the distance between the two singularities falls below the plank length?

snippet.textDisplay:
DNW (Did Not Watch, because the premise is absurd.)
The formation of axions requires the extremely hypothetical concept of C-Symmetry, the inversion of charges. Demonstrably, this does not happen. If it did, then the anti-matter, matter with inverted charges, formed from this inversion process and surrounded by, if not bound to, other matter would cause an immediate discharge of the anti-matter and an equal proportion of matter. BOOM! That's all there would be. BOOM! Axions do not exist because they cannot exist.
For a better explanation of particle integration and an explanation of the formation of first- and late-generation universal expansions (a similar process over scale) check out these short clips.

https://youtu.be/bZUnJUadNPc
https://youtu.be/qo-xblXo6Q8
https://youtu.be/70wMu_NMc0Q
